definition.value: The organophosphate oxoanion which results from the removal of two protons from the phosphate group of 3'-AMP; major species at pH 7.3.
A polyacrylamide polymer, composed of poly(N-dodecylacrylamide) macromolecules.
A polyacrylamide polymer, composed of poly(acrylamide) macromolecules.

A synthetic 36-amino acid peptide consisting of  N-acetyltyrosyl, threonyl, seryl, leucyl, isoleucyl, histidyl, seryl, leucyl, isoleucyl, alpha-glutamyl, alpha-glutamyl, seryl, glutaminyl, asparaginyl, glutaminyl, glutaminyl, alpha-glutamyl, lysyl, asparaginyl, alpha-glutamyl, alpha-glutamyl, alpha-glutamyl, leucyl, leucyl, alpha-glutamyl, leucyl, alpha-aspartyl, lysyl, tryptophyl, alanyl, seryl, leucyl, tryptophyl, asparaginyl, tryptophyl, and phenylalaninamide residues joined in sequence. An HIV fusion inhibitor, it was the first of a novel class of antiretroviral drugs used in combination therapy for the treatment of HIV-1 infection. It interferes with entry of HIV into cells by binding to the gp41 sub-unit of the viral envelope glycoprotein, so inhibiting fusion of viral and cellular membranes.
A poly(acrylamide) polymer, composed of poly(N-isopropylacrylamide) macromolecules.
A polyacrylamide polymer, composed of poly(N-n-propylacrylamide) macromolecules.
A 6-(2-aminophenyl)-2-hydroxy-6-oxohexa-2,4-dienoate in which the two double bonds adopt E,E-configuration.
A 2-hydroxypenta-2,4-dienoate in which the double bond between positions 2 and 3 has E- (cis-) geometry.
A 3-hydroxyaspartic acid that has R configuration at the carbon bearing the amino group.
A polyamino carboxylic acid in which bis(carboxymethyl)nitrilo groups are bonded to C-2 and C-2' of 1,1'-[ethane-1,2-diylbis(oxy)]dibenzene.
A polyamino carboxylic acid, the structure of which is that of BAPTA carrying methyl substituents at C-5 and C-5'.
A polyamino carboxylic acid, the structure of which is that of BAPTA carrying bromine substituents at C-5 and C-5'.
A polyacrylamide polymer, composed of poly[2-(acrylamido)-2-methyl-1-propanesulfonic acid] macromolecules.
An amino acid containing one or more nitrogen atoms connected through carbon atoms to one or more carboxy groups.
A 3-hydroxy-D-aspartic acid in which the carbon bearing the hydroxy substituent has S configuration.
A D-alpha-amino acid anion which is obtained from (3S)-3-hydroxy-D-aspartic acid by formal deprotonation of both carboxyl groups and protonation of the amino group.
Any alpha-amino acid anion in which the parent amino acid has D-configuration.
A polyacrylamide polymer, composed of poly(hexafluorobutyl methacrylamide) macromolecules.
A 3-hydroxy-D-aspartic acid in which the carbon bearing the hydroxy substituent has R configuration.
A D-alpha-amino acid anion which is obtained from (3R)-3-hydroxy-D-aspartic acid by formal deprotonation of both carboxyl groups and protonation of the amino group.
The ubiquinol corresponding to ubiquinone-0.
A D-ribityl derivative of pteridine that is a potent inhibitor of riboflavin synthetase.
An EC 2.5.1.* (non-methyl-alkyl or aryl transferase) inhibitor that inhibits the action of riboflavin synthase (EC 2.5.1.9).
A hydrochloride comprising equimolar amounts of ophenadrine and hydrogen chloride.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion which results from the removal of a proton from each of the carboxylic acid groups of N-(4-aminobenzoyl)-L-glutamic acid.
An amino acid zwitterion arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of 4-hydroxy-L-threonine; major species at pH 7.3.
A heteronuclear cluster comprising two or more metal atoms and both bridging sulfur and oxygen ligands.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of metoclopramide dihydrochloride.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with one of the carboxy groups of (2S)-ethylmalonic acid.
The (2R)-enantiomer of 2-hydroxy-2-methylbutanenitrile.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate, diphosphate and carboxy groups of (2S)-ethylmalonyl-CoA.
A C-glycosyl compound comprising a glycosylphytoceramide where the anomeric oxygen from the glycosyl moiety is replaced by carbon
A racemate is an equimolar mixture of a pair of enantiomers.
A  thiazolidinemonocarboxylic acid obtained via hydrolysis of the beta-lactam ring of amoxicillin.
A sialoheptaosylceramide where the sialoheptaosyl portion contains three sialic acid residues.
A ganglioside in which the oligosaccharide portion is composed of a heptasaccharide, to which one or more sialic acid residues are attached.
A mixture composed of two or more diastereoisomers (stereoisomers not related as mirror images).
A thirty-two membered mycolic acid consisting of 3-hydroxystearic acid having a tetradecyl group at the 2-position.
An aromatic ether, being the (2R)-3-(tert-butylamino)-2-hydroxypropyl ether of the phenolic hydroxy group of (6R,7S)-5,6,7,8-tetrahydronaphthalene-1,6,7-triol.
An aromatic ether, being the (2S)-3-(tert-butylamino)-2-hydroxypropyl ether of the phenolic hydroxy group of (6S,7R)-5,6,7,8-tetrahydronaphthalene-1,6,7-triol.
An aromatic ether, being the (2R)-3-(tert-butylamino)-2-hydroxypropyl ether of the phenolic hydroxy group of (6S,7R)-5,6,7,8-tetrahydronaphthalene-1,6,7-triol.
An aromatic ether, being the (2S)-3-(tert-butylamino)-2-hydroxypropyl ether of the phenolic hydroxy group of (6R,7S)-5,6,7,8-tetrahydronaphthalene-1,6,7-triol.
A forty-six membered mycolic acid consisting of 3-hydroxydotriacontanoic acid having a tetradecyl group at the 2-position.
A sulfated glycosaminoglycan, a linear polymer that consists of the repeating disaccharide  [3)-beta-Gal-(1->4)-beta-GlcNAc-(1->] and containing sulfo groups located at random positions.
A 6-O-acyl-D-glucose where the acyl group is 3-hydroxy-2-tetradecyldotriacontanoyl.
Any  amino sugar that is a monosaccharide in which one alcoholic hydroxy group is replaced by an amino group.
